---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import SectionDivider from "../components/SectionDivider.astro";
import Button from "../components/Button.astro";

const scheduleUrl = "https://homeopathyhelpnow.com/services/";

const contactEmail =
  "mailto:Mindy@DivineHealthHomeopathy.com?subject=Question%20About%20Classical%20Homeopathy&body=Hello%20Mindy%2C%0A%0AI%20have%20a%20question%20about%20classical%20homeopathy%3A%0A%0A";
---

<Layout
  title="Frequently Asked Questions | Divine Health Homeopathy"
  description="Explore thoughtful answers to common questions about individualized classical homeopathy, homeopathic remedies, children and families, and the history of homeopathy."
>
  <main>

    <!-- Historical hero -->
    <section class="faq-hero">
      <div class="faq-hero-inner">

        <figure class="letter-figure">
          <div class="letter-frame">
            <img
              src="/images/history/hahnemann-truth-letter.jpg"
              alt="Facsimile of an autograph letter written by Samuel Hahnemann in Paris on March 12, 1843"
            />
          </div>

          <figcaption>
            Autograph letter written by Samuel Hahnemann in Paris on March 12,
            1843, to his sister-in-law, Madame D'Hervilly.
            The&nbsp;letter&nbsp;was&nbsp;written&nbsp;in&nbsp;English,&nbsp;German,&nbsp;and&nbsp;French.

            <br /><br />

            Reproduced from
            <cite>
              The Hom&oelig;opathic Physician: Journal of Medical Science
            </cite>,
            April&nbsp;11,&nbsp;1895.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <div class="hero-copy">
          <p class="eyebrow">The Search for Truth</p>

          <h1>Questions are welcomed.</h1>

          <div class="hero-divider">
            <SectionDivider />
          </div>

          <blockquote>
            <p>
              &ldquo;I sought truth earnestly and found it.&rdquo;
            </p>

            <cite>Samuel Hahnemann</cite>
          </blockquote>

          <p class="hero-intro">
            Classical homeopathy was shaped through careful observation,
            rigorous questioning, and a lifelong search for truth. Whether you
            are completely new to homeopathy, thoughtfully skeptical, or simply
            curious to learn more, your questions are an important part of the
            journey.
          </p>
        </div>

      </div>
    </section>


    <!-- What is classical homeopathy -->
    <section class="faq-topic faq-topic-classical">
      <div class="faq-topic-inner">

        <div class="topic-feature">
          <figure class="topic-image classical-image">
            <img
              src="/images/history/apothecary-still-life.jpg"
              alt="Black-and-white still life with antique Boericke and Tafel pharmacy bottles, homeopathic books, mortar and pestle, candle, and remedy vial"
            />

            <figcaption>
  Original <cite>Boericke &amp; Tafel&rsquo;s Triturations </cite>
  homeopathic pharmacy bottle labeled Hydrastin 2X, dated
  December&nbsp;21,&nbsp;1936, pictured at left. Photographed alongside a
  well-worn twentieth-century printing of Samuel Hahnemann&rsquo;s
  <cite> Organon of Medicine, Sixth Edition</cite>, translated by
  William Boericke, M.D.
</figcaption>
          </figure>

          <div class="topic-heading">
            <p class="eyebrow">Foundational Questions</p>

            <h2>What is classical homeopathy?</h2>

            <div class="divider-left">
              <SectionDivider />
            </div>

            <p>
              Classical homeopathy is an individualized system of medicine
              centered on careful observation and the complete symptom picture
              of the person. These questions explore the principles that
              distinguish classical homeopathy from other approaches to health
              and wellness.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-list">

  <details open>
    <summary>
      <span>What is classical homeopathy?</span>
      <span class="faq-symbol" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
    </summary>

    <div class="faq-answer">
      <p>
        Classical Homeopathy is an individualized system of medicine founded
        by the German physician Dr. Samuel Hahnemann. Rather than treating a
        diagnosis alone, Classical Homeopathy considers the complete picture
        of a person&rsquo;s physical, mental, and emotional symptoms to select
        a single remedy uniquely matched to the individual. Homeopathy is used by more than 200 million people worldwide and is
        practiced in over 100 countries, making it one of the world&rsquo;s
        most widely used systems of healthcare.
      </p>

      <p>
        Classical Homeopathy is founded on the
        <strong> Law of Similars</strong>, expressed in the Latin phrase
        <em> similia similibus curentur</em>&mdash;&ldquo;let like be cured by
        like.&rdquo; Through careful observation and experimentation,
        Hahnemann realized that a substance capable of producing symptoms in a
        healthy person could stimulate healing in someone experiencing a
        similar pattern of symptoms.
      </p>

      <p>
        In 1807, he coined the term <em>homeopathy</em>, derived from the Greek
        words <em>homoios</em> (&ldquo;similar&rdquo;) and
        <em> pathos</em> (&ldquo;suffering&rdquo;), in one of his first essays on the subject which was published in <em>Hufeland&rsquo;s Medical Journal</em>, written in German.
      </p>

      <p>
        Today, Classical Homeopathy continues to follow the principles first
        laid out by Hahnemann over two centuries ago, emphasizing careful
        observation, individualized treatment, and respect for the
        body&rsquo;s natural capacity to restore health.
      </p>
    </div>
  </details>

          <details>
            <summary>
              <span>What does individualized care mean?</span>
              <span class="faq-symbol" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
            </summary>

            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                Individualized care means that two people with the same
                diagnosis may receive different homeopathic remedies. Although
                the diagnosis may be shared, the people experiencing it may
                differ in their symptom patterns, sensitivities, energy,
                temperament, and overall health histories.
              </p>

              <p>
                The remedy is chosen for the individual rather than assigned
                automatically according to the condition.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details>
            <summary>
              <span>
                Why might two people with the same diagnosis receive different
                remedies?
              </span>

              <span class="faq-symbol" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
            </summary>

            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                A diagnosis describes a condition, but it does not always
                describe the unique way that condition is experienced. One
                person may feel better from warmth while another prefers cold.
                One may become restless, while another wants quiet and
                solitude. One person&rsquo;s symptoms may be worse at night,
                while another&rsquo;s appear in the morning.
              </p>

              <p>
                Those individualizing details help distinguish one case from
                another.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details>
            <summary>
              <span>What does &ldquo;one remedy at a time&rdquo; mean?</span>
              <span class="faq-symbol" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
            </summary>

            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                In Classical Homeopathy, one carefully selected remedy is
                generally given at a time. This allows the response to be
                observed clearly without introducing several remedies
                simultaneously.
              </p>

              <p>
                The remedy may then be repeated, adjusted, changed, or simply
                allowed more time depending on the individual&rsquo;s response.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details>
            <summary>
              <span>
                How is homeopathy different from herbal medicine or supplements?
              </span>

              <span class="faq-symbol" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
            </summary>

            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                Homeopathy, herbal medicine, and nutritional supplementation
                are distinct approaches. Herbal products generally contain
                measurable plant constituents, while supplements provide
                nutrients or other substances in material doses.
              </p>

              <p>
                Homeopathic remedies are prepared through a specialized process
                of serial dilution and succussion and are selected according to
                the individualized symptom picture.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details>
            <summary>
              <span>Why is classical homeopathy considered holistic?</span>
              <span class="faq-symbol" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
            </summary>

            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                Classical Homeopathy considers the person as an integrated
                whole. Physical symptoms are important, but they are considered
                together with sleep, energy, appetite, temperature preferences,
                emotional responses, personal tendencies, and health history.
              </p>

              <p>
                The goal is to understand the relationship among the symptoms
                rather than viewing each one as an isolated event.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>

        </div>
      </div>
    </section>


    <!-- Understanding the remedies -->
    <section class="faq-topic faq-topic-remedies">
      <div class="faq-topic-inner">

        <div class="topic-feature topic-feature-reverse">
          <div class="topic-heading">
            <p class="eyebrow">Homeopathic Pharmacy</p>

            <h2>Understanding the remedies</h2>

            <div class="divider-left">
              <SectionDivider />
            </div>

            <p>
              Homeopathic remedies have a history, language, and method of
              preparation that may be unfamiliar at first. These questions
              explain where remedies originate, how they are prepared, and how
              their use is individualized.
            </p>
          </div>

          <figure class="topic-image remedies-image">
            <img
              src="/images/history/mindy-study-collection.jpg"
              alt="Mindy's homeopathic study collection with the Organon of Medicine, materia medica, antique Boericke and Tafel bottle, mortar and pestle, candle, and remedy vial"
            />

           <figcaption>
  <strong>Tools of the Trade. </strong>
  Original <cite>Boericke &amp; Tafel&rsquo;s Triturations </cite>
  homeopathic pharmacy bottle labeled Apium Virus 12X, dated
  August&nbsp;8,&nbsp;1922, pictured at left. A mortar and pestle, glass
  bottles, handwritten notes, and carefully prepared remedies recall the
  early history of pharmacy and homeopathy.
</figcaption> 
          </figure>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-list">

          <details>
            <summary>
              <span>What are homeopathic remedies made from?</span>
              <span class="faq-symbol" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
            </summary>

            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                Homeopathic remedies may originate from substances found in the
                mineral, plant, or animal kingdoms. The original substance is
                prepared according to established homeopathic pharmacy methods.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details>
            <summary>
              <span>How are homeopathic remedies prepared?</span>
              <span class="faq-symbol" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
            </summary>

            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                Remedies are prepared through repeated steps of dilution and
                succussion, a controlled shaking process. The sequence and
                scale of preparation are represented by the potency printed on
                the remedy label.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details>
            <summary>
              <span>What is trituration?</span>
              <span class="faq-symbol" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
            </summary>

            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                Trituration is a traditional pharmacy process in which an
                insoluble substance is repeatedly ground with lactose according
                to a defined ratio. This allows the substance to be prepared
                through the early stages of homeopathic potentization before
                further preparation may continue in liquid form.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details>
            <summary>
              <span>Why are homeopathic pellets so small?</span>
              <span class="faq-symbol" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
            </summary>

            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                The small pellets act as carriers for the prepared homeopathic
                remedy. The size of the pellet does not determine the selected
                potency or the appropriateness of the remedy for an individual
                case.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details>
            <summary>
              <span>How should remedies be stored?</span>
              <span class="faq-symbol" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
            </summary>

            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                Remedies are generally stored in their original containers in a
                cool, dry place away from direct sunlight, strong odors,
                excessive heat, and moisture. Any specific storage guidance
                supplied by the pharmacy or practitioner should also be
                followed.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details>
            <summary>
              <span>Why are remedies not always taken every day?</span>
              <span class="faq-symbol" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
            </summary>

            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                The timing and repetition of a remedy depend on the individual
                case, the potency, the nature of the concern, and the response
                being observed. In some situations a remedy may be repeated; in
                others, a single dose may be followed by a period of careful
                observation.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>

        </div>
      </div>
    </section>


    <!-- Children and families -->
    <section class="faq-topic faq-topic-families">
      <div class="faq-topic-inner">

        <header class="section-heading">
          <p class="eyebrow">Children &amp; Families</p>

          <h2>Homeopathy across the stages of life</h2>

          <SectionDivider />

          <p>
            Individualized homeopathic care considers each person&rsquo;s
            complete symptom picture, whether the client is an infant, child,
            adolescent, or adult.
          </p>
        </header>

        <div class="faq-list">

          <details>
            <summary>
              <span>Can children receive individualized homeopathic care?</span>
              <span class="faq-symbol" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
            </summary>

            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                Children may receive individualized homeopathic consultations.
                A parent or legal guardian participates in the consultation and
                provides health history, observations, and information about
                the child&rsquo;s symptoms and general tendencies.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details>
            <summary>
              <span>Can infants receive homeopathic care?</span>
              <span class="faq-symbol" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
            </summary>

            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                Infants may also be considered for individualized homeopathic
                care. Because infants cannot describe their experiences
                verbally, the observations of parents and caregivers become
                especially important.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details>
            <summary>
              <span>Can several members of one family receive care?</span>
              <span class="faq-symbol" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
            </summary>

            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                Yes. Each family member is considered as a separate,
                individualized case. Even relatives who share similar concerns
                may express their symptoms differently and may therefore
                require different remedies.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details>
            <summary>
              <span>Do children receive the same remedies as adults?</span>
              <span class="faq-symbol" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
            </summary>

            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>
                A remedy is selected according to the individual symptom
                picture rather than age alone. Children and adults may
                sometimes receive the same remedy, but only when it
                appropriately corresponds to the individual case.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>

        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Final CTA -->
    <section class="faq-cta">
      <div class="cta-inner">
        <p class="eyebrow">Still Have Questions?</p>

        <h2>Your questions are welcome.</h2>

        <SectionDivider />

        <p>
        Every person&rsquo;s health story is unique. Whether you are exploring
        classical homeopathy for the first time or are ready to begin your own
        journey, I invite you to continue learning or reach out with your
        questions.
        </p>

        <div class="cta-actions">
        <Button href="/resources" variant="primary">
        Explore Resources
        </Button>

  <Button
    href={scheduleUrl}
    target="_blank"
    variant="gold"
  >
    Schedule a Consultation
    </Button>
    </div>
      </div>
    </section>

  </main>
</Layout>

<style>
  main {
    overflow: hidden;
  }

  /*
   * Shared typography
   */

  .eyebrow {
    margin: 0 0 15px;

    color: var(--gold);
    font-size: 0.86rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.34em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  h1,
  h2,
  h3 {
    color: var(--navy);
  }

  h1 {
    margin: 0;

    font-size: clamp(3.5rem, 6vw, 5.8rem);
    line-height: 0.98;
  }

  h2 {
    margin: 0;

    font-size: clamp(2.65rem, 4.7vw, 4rem);
    line-height: 1.06;
  }

  cite {
    font-style: italic;
  }

  .divider-left {
    width: max-content;
    margin-top: 24px;
  }

  /*
   * Historical hero
   */

  .faq-hero {
    padding: 72px 40px 78px;

    background:
      radial-gradient(
        circle at top right,
        #fffdf8 0%,
        #f5ead9 58%,
        #ead9c1 100%
      );
  }

  .faq-hero-inner {
    max-width: 1180px;
    margin: 0 auto;

    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 0.82fr 1.18fr;
    gap: 68px;
    align-items: center;
  }

  .letter-figure {
    margin: 0;
  }

  .letter-frame {
    padding: 12px;

    background: #f8efdf;
    border: 1px solid #d7c29f;

    box-shadow:
      0 24px 58px rgba(16, 35, 63, 0.13);

    transform: rotate(-1deg);
  }

  .letter-frame img {
    display: block;

    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    max-height: 610px;

    object-fit: contain;
    object-position: center;

    filter:
      sepia(0.08)
      saturate(0.86)
      contrast(0.98);
  }

  .letter-figure figcaption {
    margin-top: 14px;

    color: #746957;
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    font-style: normal;
    line-height: 1.6;
    text-align: center;
  }

  .letter-figure figcaption cite {
    display: inline;

    color: #665b4d;
    font-style: italic;
    font-weight: 500;
    letter-spacing: 0.015em;
  }

  .hero-divider {
    width: max-content;
    margin: 24px 0;
  }

  .hero-copy blockquote {
    margin: 25px 0;
    padding-left: 25px;

    border-left: 3px solid var(--gold);
  }

  .hero-copy blockquote p {
    margin: 0;

    color: var(--navy);
    font-family: Georgia, "Times New Roman", serif;
    font-size: clamp(1.75rem, 3.1vw, 2.65rem);
    font-style: italic;
    line-height: 1.36;
  }

  .hero-copy blockquote cite {
    display: block;
    margin-top: 12px;

    color: #756b5c;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    font-style: normal;
  }

  .hero-intro {
    max-width: 650px;
    margin: 0;

    color: #40516a;
    font-size: 1.15rem;
    line-height: 1.82;
  }

  /*
   * Shared FAQ topic sections
   */

  .faq-topic {
    padding: 82px 40px;
  }

  .faq-topic-inner {
    max-width: 1120px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }

  .faq-topic-classical {
    background: #fffdf9;
  }

  .faq-topic-remedies {
    background:
      radial-gradient(
        circle at top,
        #fffaf2 0%,
        #f1e4d2 100%
      );
  }

  .faq-topic-families {
    background: #fffdf9;
  }

  /*
 * Image-and-heading feature rows
 */

.topic-feature {
  margin-bottom: 52px;

  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 0.98fr 1.02fr;
  gap: 48px;
  align-items: center;
}

.topic-feature-reverse {
  grid-template-columns: 1.02fr 0.98fr;
}

.topic-heading > p:last-child {
  max-width: 560px;
  margin: 24px 0 0;

  color: #46566d;
  font-size: 1.08rem;
  line-height: 1.8;
}

.topic-image {
  margin: 0;
  text-align: center;
}

.topic-image img {
  display: block;

  width: auto;
  max-width: 100%;
  height: auto;
  max-height: 560px;
  margin: 0 auto;

  border: 5px solid rgba(255, 253, 249, 0.82);
  border-radius: 14px;

  box-shadow:
    0 20px 46px rgba(16, 35, 63, 0.12);
}

.topic-image figcaption {
  max-width: 590px;
  margin: 13px auto 0;

  color: #746957;
  font-size: 0.79rem;
  font-style: normal;
  line-height: 1.58;
  text-align: center;
}

.topic-image figcaption cite {
  color: #665b4d;
  font-style: italic;
  font-weight: 500;
}

.topic-image figcaption strong {
  color: #665b4d;
  font-weight: 700;
  letter-spacing: 0.03em;
}

/*
 * Section headings without images
 */

  .section-heading {
    max-width: 800px;
    margin: 0 auto 42px;

    text-align: center;
  }

  .section-heading h2 {
    margin-bottom: 23px;
  }

  .section-heading > p:last-child {
    max-width: 680px;
    margin: 24px auto 0;

    color: #526176;
    font-size: 1.06rem;
    line-height: 1.74;
  }

  /*
   * FAQ accordions
   */

  .faq-list {
    display: grid;
    gap: 13px;
  }

  details {
    overflow: hidden;

    background: rgba(255, 253, 249, 0.82);
    border: 1px solid #dfd1ba;
    border-radius: 19px;

    box-shadow:
      0 10px 26px rgba(16, 35, 63, 0.05);

    transition:
      border-color 0.25s ease,
      box-shadow 0.25s ease,
      transform 0.25s ease;
  }

  details:hover {
    border-color: rgba(184, 154, 94, 0.48);

    transform: translateY(-2px);
  }

  details[open] {
    border-color: rgba(184, 154, 94, 0.56);

    box-shadow:
      0 14px 34px rgba(16, 35, 63, 0.08);
  }

  summary {
    padding: 21px 25px;

    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: space-between;
    gap: 22px;

    color: var(--navy);
    font-size: 1.12rem;
    font-weight: 700;

    cursor: pointer;
    list-style: none;
  }

  summary::-webkit-details-marker {
    display: none;
  }

  .faq-symbol {
    flex: 0 0 auto;

    color: var(--gold);
    font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    font-weight: 400;

    transition: transform 0.25s ease;
  }

  details[open] .faq-symbol {
    transform: rotate(45deg);
  }

  .faq-answer {
    padding: 0 25px 23px;
  }

  .faq-answer p {
    margin: 0 0 14px;

    color: #526176;
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.75;
  }

  .faq-answer p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  /*
   * Final CTA
   */

  .faq-cta {
  padding: 92px 40px 96px;

  background:
    radial-gradient(
      circle at top,
      #fffaf1 0%,
      #ecddc8 100%
    );
}

.cta-inner {
  max-width: 820px;
  margin: 0 auto;
  text-align: center;
}

.cta-inner h2 {
  margin-bottom: 28px;
}

  .cta-inner > p:last-of-type {
  max-width: 700px;
  margin: 28px auto 0;

  color: #46566d;
  font-size: 1.12rem;
  line-height: 1.82;
  text-align: center;
}

  .cta-actions {
    margin-top: 30px;

    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    gap: 16px;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }

  /*
   * Tablet
   */

  @media (max-width: 940px) {
    .faq-hero-inner,
    .topic-feature,
    .topic-feature-reverse {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      gap: 42px;
    }

    .faq-hero-inner {
      max-width: 760px;
    }

    .letter-frame img {
      max-height: 680px;
    }

    .hero-copy,
    .topic-heading {
      text-align: center;
    }

    .hero-divider,
    .divider-left {
      margin-left: auto;
      margin-right: auto;
    }

    .hero-copy blockquote {
      padding: 0;

      border-left: 0;
    }

    .hero-intro,
    .topic-heading > p:last-child {
      margin-left: auto;
      margin-right: auto;
    }

    .topic-image {
      width: 100%;
      max-width: 720px;
      margin: 0 auto;
    }

    .topic-feature-reverse .topic-heading {
      order: 2;
    }

